    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv. For each file, parse the timestamp column with pd.to_datetime(..., unit='s', utc=True) and return a compact summary containing: 1) total row count; 2) minimum and maximum timestamp (in UTC datetime string); 3) list of unique cmdb_id values (all); 4) list of unique KPI/trace/log name values (for metric.csv use kpi_name; for trace.csv use trace_name; for log.csv use log_name; for error_logs.csv there is no KPI name so skip this list). Limit each list of names to at most top 20 entries. Present the results as a small table or dictionary per file. Do not print full raw tables."}

{
    "analysis": "Previous step loaded the four telemetry files and produced compact summaries. Observations: metric.csv and trace.csv cover 2024-01-17T12:06:00 → 12:30:00 UTC (so metrics/traces start after the incident window start 12:03:28 but still cover most of the incident window until 12:33:28). log.csv has same metric time coverage. error_logs.csv contains 12 rows from frontend only between 12:18:49→12:29:59 UTC. Next we must follow the prescribed workflow: compute global thresholds for each component-KPI using the full metric series (not filtered), then filter to the incident window and detect anomalies. The immediate goal is to find which component-KPI pairs exceed their global thresholds during the incident window (candidate faults).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv only: 1) Parse timestamp as UTC datetimes. 2) For each unique (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pair compute the global P95 threshold using all rows for that pair in the file (do NOT filter by incident window for threshold calculation). 3) Then filter metric rows to the incident window 2024-01-17 12:03:28 UTC → 2024-01-17 12:33:28 UTC. 4) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pair, identify rows in the incident window where value >= P95 threshold (treat equality as anomaly). 5) Return a compact table (limit 20 rows) of candidate pairs that have at least one anomaly in the window, with these columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, p95_threshold, total_points_in_window, anomaly_count_in_window, anomaly_fraction_in_window (anomaly_count / total_points), earliest_anomaly_timestamp_utc (ISO format), max_value_in_window. Sort the output by anomaly_count descending, then anomaly_fraction, then earliest_anomaly_timestamp. If no pairs exceed P95, also compute and return the same table using P90 (i.e., retry with P90) and label which threshold was used." }

{
    "analysis": "From metric analysis we found pervasive socket anomalies across many services. However, per the diagnosis rules the root-cause must be chosen from the provided candidate services (checkoutservice, currencyservice, emailservice, productcatalogservice, recommendationservice). We must now use traces to disambiguate which of these service-level components is the most downstream faulty component (if multiple are flagged by metrics). Next step: analyze trace telemetry only for these five candidate services to see which trace features exceed their global thresholds during the incident window and to identify downstream call relationships and timings. This will help pick the most likely root-cause service among the candidates.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load trace.csv. For only these cmdb_id values: checkoutservice, currencyservice, emailservice, productcatalogservice, recommendationservice — 1) compute the global P95 threshold for each (cmdb_id, trace_name) using the entire trace.csv (do NOT filter first); 2) then filter trace rows to the incident window 2024-01-17 12:03:28 UTC → 2024-01-17 12:33:28 UTC; 3) for each (cmdb_id, trace_name) report if any point in the window has value >= P95. Return a compact table (limit 20 rows) with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, p95_threshold, total_points_in_window, anomaly_count_in_window, anomaly_fraction_in_window, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_utc (ISO), max_value_in_window. Sort by anomaly_count desc then anomaly_fraction desc then earliest_anomaly_timestamp. If no anomalies at P95 for these services, retry the same using P90 and indicate which threshold was used." }

{
    "analysis": "Trace analysis (last step) computed global P95 per (service, trace_name) and checked for anomalies in the incident window for the five candidate services. Results show many trace error_rate series flagged because their P95 is 0.0 and window values equal 0.0, which makes these detections uninformative (threshold-equality artifact). Combined with metric analysis, multiple services (checkoutservice, currencyservice, emailservice, recommendationservice, and to a lesser extent productcatalogservice) show socket-related metric anomalies, many with anomaly_fraction = 1.0. According to the diagnosis rules, when multiple service-level components are faulty we should use traces and logs to pick the most downstream faulty service in the call chain and to identify the failure reason. The traces we checked for error_rate are not discriminative due to zero thresholds. Next, we need to use logs (log.csv) and textual error logs (error_logs.csv) filtered to the incident window to find explicit socket/connection errors or other messages that indicate the failure reason and to see which candidate service(s) show concrete error messages. Additionally, in trace data we should inspect latency/duration trace features (not just error_rate) for the candidate services if logs are not decisive. ",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load log.csv and error_logs.csv. Parse timestamps as UTC datetimes and filter rows to the incident window 2024-01-17 12:03:28 UTC → 2024-01-17 12:33:28 UTC. 1) For log.csv: group by cmdb_id and log_name and compute (a) total_points_in_window, (b) sum_value_in_window, (c) max_value_in_window, (d) earliest_timestamp_in_window where value>0 (if any). Return at most top 20 groups where sum_value_in_window>0 sorted by sum_value_in_window desc. Include the columns: cmdb_id, log_name, total_points_in_window, sum_value_in_window, max_value_in_window, earliest_positive_ts_utc. 2) For error_logs.csv: return (a) total row count in window, (b) list of unique cmdb_id values and counts per cmdb_id, (c) up to 20 sample rows with columns timestamp_utc, cmdb_id, message. 3) Additionally, search error_logs.csv messages (within the window) for socket/connection-related keywords: ['socket','connect','connection','timeout','refused','ECONN'] (case-insensitive). For each matching keyword group, report the count of matching rows and up to 5 sample messages with timestamps and cmdb_id. Limit outputs to keep results compact." }

I reviewed the metric, trace, and log analyses: pervasive socket KPI anomalies across services, high-severity trace duration spikes focused on productcatalogservice (notably at ~12:18–12:20 UTC), and frontend errors indicating downstream failures. These together point to productcatalogservice experiencing socket-level failures that increased request latencies and caused downstream errors.

